            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-09-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-09-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="103" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d103">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/9–1946: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-09-19">September 19,
                            1946</date>.<lb/>[Received September 20—7:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1502. In a press conference September 17 Communist spokesman Wang Ping-nan in
                    Nanking stated that unless Govt complies with Communist request for resumption
                    of Committee of Three conversations there will be no reason for conversations
                    and hence no necessity for General Chou En-lai to return to Nanking from
                    Shanghai.</p>
                <p>Wang denied Communists were receiving any Soviet aid or would accept it at any
                    time in the future. He stated Communist prerequisite now is cease fire
                    agreement, that Govt cannot win due to lack of Kuomintang army morale and
                    economic conditions and that Govt is now determined to force a military solution
                    if possible.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
